The polynomial \( P(x) \) has roots at \( x = 1, 2, 3, \ldots, 10 \). These roots divide the number line into 11 intervals. The leading term of \( P(x) \) is \( x^{1+2+3+\cdots+10} = x^{55} \), which is positive for large \( x \). For each interval \( (r, r+1) \), the sign of \( P(x) \) is determined by the product of the signs of each factor \( (x - k)^{m_k} \). A root \( k \) with an odd multiplicity will cause a sign change in the polynomial when passing through the root. We calculate the sign of \( P(x) \) in each interval by considering the sum of the multiplicities of the roots greater than the current interval. The sign in each interval \( (r, r+1) \) is given by \( (-1)^{\text{sum of multiplicities of roots greater than } r} \). Key steps: 1. The sign of \( P(x) \) in the interval \( (10, \infty) \) is positive. 2.
